"Although he never played in a Super Bowl, Boselli did star on a national stage when he stonewalled Buffalo Bills defensive end Bruce Smith during a 30-27 playoff win in December 1996. Smith, who remains the NFL's all-time sack leader with 200, was at the top of his game that season. His 13 1/2 sacks were part of a seven-year run during which Smith notched at least 10 sacks. Boselli made Smith a non-factor.",

"Boselli was often his best while going up against the best around the league. An often-told story by TV analyst Phil Simms about Boselli goes back to the start of the 1998 season. Kansas City Chiefs linebacker/defensive end Derrick Thomas had six sacks during a win over Oakland the first week of the season with a game against the Jaguars up next. Simms asked Tom Coughlin, who was coach of the Jaguars at the time, what he was planning to do to stop Thomas. \"We'll let them go one-on-one, then we'll see who wins the battle,\" Coughlin said of Boselli and Thomas. Boselli won; Thomas had zero sacks, and the Jaguars won the game.",

"Critics often point to Boselli playing just seven seasons as a reason why he should not be in the Pro Football Hall of Fame, but he accomplished quite a bit during that time. Boselli was selected to the Pro Bowl five years in a row from 1996-2000 and was named to the NFL's all-decade team of the 1990s even though he only played for half of it. Boselli was named to the AP and Pro Football Writers All-Pro teams in 1997 and 1999.",

"Players of Boselli's time respect him. A few quotes: \"He's in the same category with Willie Roaf and Anthony Munoz and Johnathan Ogden and Walter Jones - he's equal to all those guys,\" former Dallas Cowboys scout Gil Brandt said. \"My opinion is that he is one of the best offensive tackles I have observed,\" Munoz said. \"He was the only offensive tackle I respected besides my teammate Johnathan Ogden. He was an All-Pro defensive player lining up at tackle. He attacked you,\" former Baltimore Ravens defensive end Michael McCrary said. \"Even though I had two years on him, he was someone I would watch and gauge my game after,\" Roaf said.",

"Boselli was known as the leader of the Jaguars, who went from an expansion team in 1995 to playing in the AFC Championship Game a year later. The Jaguars made the playoffs four straight seasons and also played in the AFC Championship Game in 1999. \"Look at the numbers,\" Coughlin said. \"When you look at his numbers there isn't any question. Now you have other guys that played more, but they still, he gave up fewer sacks. All the things you would ask a left tackle to do [he did it] better than a bunch of those guys who are in the Hall.\"",
